580
00:38:11,976 --> 00:38:15,070
Japan, of course.
Couple of places in Europe.

581
00:38:15,146 --> 00:38:18,274
You'd almost certainly find it
somewhere in Paris...

582
00:38:18,349 --> 00:38:20,977
Rome, Amsterdam.

583
00:38:21,052 --> 00:38:22,349
Maybe London.

584
00:38:22,420 --> 00:38:26,618
This bouquet was hand engineered
to someone's specifications.

585
00:38:26,691 --> 00:38:28,352
Is there any way
of knowing which shops?

586
00:38:28,426 --> 00:38:30,451
Of course.
We'll give you a list.

587
00:38:30,528 --> 00:38:32,393
It'll be short.

588
00:38:44,742 --> 00:38:47,074
I need opera tickets.

589
00:38:47,144 --> 00:38:49,203
I don't think I got any on me.

590
00:38:49,280 --> 00:38:51,214
It's sold out,
whatever it's called.

591
00:38:51,282 --> 00:38:53,978
It's the pretty, young wife
with the ever-open beak...

592
00:38:54,051 --> 00:38:56,246
who needs opera tickets.

593
00:39:04,662 --> 00:39:05,754
Benetti.

594
00:39:05,830 --> 00:39:07,058
What?

595
00:39:07,131 --> 00:39:08,598
Rewind it.

596
00:39:08,666 --> 00:39:09,963
I can't rewind it.

597
00:39:10,034 --> 00:39:12,935
I'm making a copy.
I'm recording.

598
00:39:23,247 --> 00:39:24,271
What is this?

599
00:39:24,348 --> 00:39:27,476
Camera from a perfume shop
on Via Della Scala.

600
00:39:27,551 --> 00:39:29,542
FBI through lnterpol
requested a copy.

601
00:39:29,620 --> 00:39:31,850
-Why?
-They didn't say.

602
00:39:33,691 --> 00:39:34,783
They didn't say?

603
00:39:34,859 --> 00:39:37,123
No. It was actually
kind of weird...

604
00:39:37,194 --> 00:39:40,095
Iike they were making
a point not to say.

605
00:41:23,567 --> 00:41:25,592
Are we going to the opera?

606
00:41:27,638 --> 00:41:28,662
Sorry.

607
00:41:28,739 --> 00:41:30,104
Yes, we are going.

608
00:41:30,174 --> 00:41:31,664
You got tickets.

609
00:41:31,742 --> 00:41:33,004
No, but I will.

610
00:41:33,077 --> 00:41:36,672
In fact,
I was just about to look here.

611
00:41:36,747 --> 00:41:39,147
Please not the back row.

612
00:41:39,216 --> 00:41:42,413
I would like to see it
this time.

613
00:41:42,486 --> 00:41:44,647
Nowhere near the back row.

614
00:41:44,722 --> 00:41:46,314
No matter what the cost.

615
00:43:56,053 --> 00:43:58,487
Tell me, Clarice,
would you want to harm those...

616
00:43:58,556 --> 00:44:00,615
who've forced you
to consider it, though?

617
00:44:00,691 --> 00:44:02,955
It's perfectly OKto feel this.

618
00:44:03,027 --> 00:44:07,726
It's perfectly au naturel
to want to taste the enemy.

619
00:44:22,646 --> 00:44:24,910
It just feels so good.
Tell me, Clarice...

620
00:44:24,982 --> 00:44:27,280
what is your worst memory
of childhood?

621
00:44:27,351 --> 00:44:30,047
-Jesus, Starling!
-Can I help you, Mr. Krendler?

622
00:44:30,120 --> 00:44:32,145
What you doing
sitting in the dark?

623
00:44:32,222 --> 00:44:33,655
Thinking about cannibalism.

624
00:44:33,724 --> 00:44:36,522
People in Justice
are thinking, too.

625
00:44:36,594 --> 00:44:37,891
You know that?

626
00:44:37,962 --> 00:44:40,021
They're thinking, "What exactly
is she doing about Lecter?"

627
00:44:40,097 --> 00:44:42,497
Aren't you curious
why he dines on his victims?

628
00:44:42,566 --> 00:44:44,796
And what's the point of that?

629
00:44:44,868 --> 00:44:46,859
Are you writing a book
or you catching a crook?

630
00:44:46,937 --> 00:44:50,202
To show his contempt
for those who exasperate him.

631
00:44:51,542 --> 00:44:54,409
Or sometimes to perform
a public service.

632
00:44:54,478 --> 00:44:57,208
In the case of the flutist,
Benjamin Raspail...

633
00:44:57,281 --> 00:44:58,646
he did it
to improve the sound...

634
00:44:58,716 --> 00:45:01,412
of the Baltimore
Philharmonic Orchestra...

635
00:45:01,485 --> 00:45:03,976
serving the not-so-talented
flute player's sweetbreads...

636
00:45:04,054 --> 00:45:05,112
to the Board...

637
00:45:05,189 --> 00:45:07,453
with a nice Montrachet
at $700 a bottle.

638
00:45:10,194 --> 00:45:12,219
That meal began
with green oysters...

639
00:45:12,296 --> 00:45:13,320
from the Gironde...

640
00:45:13,397 --> 00:45:15,524
followed by the sweetbreads...

641
00:45:15,599 --> 00:45:16,759
a sorbet...

642
00:45:16,834 --> 00:45:19,462
and then you can read here
in "Gourmet Cuisine":

643
00:45:19,536 --> 00:45:21,731
"A notable dark
and glossy ragout...

644
00:45:21,805 --> 00:45:24,672
"the constituents
never determined."

645
00:45:24,742 --> 00:45:26,369
I always figured him
for a queer.

646
00:45:26,443 --> 00:45:28,308
Why would you say that, Paul?

647
00:45:28,379 --> 00:45:31,314
Well,
all this artsy-fartsy stuff.

648
00:45:31,382 --> 00:45:33,043
Chamber music, tea party food.

649
00:45:33,117 --> 00:45:35,312
Not that I mean
anything personal...

650
00:45:35,386 --> 00:45:38,651
if you've got a lot of sympathy
for those people.

651
00:45:38,722 --> 00:45:43,625
What I came here to impress
upon you, Starling...

652
00:45:43,694 --> 00:45:45,389
